Here's the most reassuring thing you'll ever hear about streaming in Spark. Structured Streaming is just a batch job, run over and over in a loop. That's it. If you already understand batch, you're most of the way there. Spark takes the new data that has arrived, runs a normal batch query on that little slice, and then waits for more. Each slice is called a micro-batch. Let's walk one full lap around the loop.

It starts with the offset tracker. Before each batch, Spark asks a simple question, what's new since last time? Every streaming source, like a Kafka topic or a folder of files, has a notion of position, an offset. Spark remembers the offset it reached in the previous run, looks at where the source is now, and the gap between them is the new data for this batch. This is how Spark knows exactly what to process and never reads the same record twice.

Next is the micro-batch trigger, which decides when each batch fires. With processing time, you say run every five seconds, or every minute, on a fixed clock. With available now, Spark processes all the data waiting right now in one or more batches and then stops, which is perfect for a scheduled job that drains a queue. And the once trigger is the simplest, run exactly one batch and quit. The trigger is your dial between true continuous processing and periodic scheduled runs.

Once Spark knows what to read and that it's time to go, we hit the part you already know, partition and process. This is the exact same engine as batch. The data is split into partitions, tasks run on executors, the same DAG and stages, everything we covered in the execution reel. There is nothing new here, and that's the whole point. Streaming reuses the batch machine.

But there's one capability batch doesn't need, and that's the state store. Many streaming questions span multiple batches. A running count, a total per user, an average over the last ten minutes. That information has to survive from one micro-batch to the next, so Spark keeps it in a state store, and modern Spark uses RocksDB for this, an embedded database on each executor. When this batch adds three to a user's running total, that updated total is saved in the state store, ready for the next batch to build on. This is what makes windowed aggregations and stateful streaming possible.

Then comes the sink and the output mode, where results go out. The output mode is the streaming-specific twist, it controls what gets written each batch. Append only writes brand new rows, and is for cases where past results never change. Update writes just the rows whose values changed since last batch, ideal for running aggregations. And complete rewrites the entire result table every time, used for smaller summaries you always want in full. Choosing the right mode is about how your result evolves over time.

And finally, the step that makes all of this trustworthy, the checkpoint save. At the end of every micro-batch, Spark writes down everything it needs to recover, the offsets it processed, a write-ahead log of what it intended to do, and the current contents of the state store. This checkpoint is the safety net. If an executor dies, or the whole job crashes and restarts, Spark reads the checkpoint, sees exactly which offsets were done and what the state was, and resumes from precisely that point. No data lost, no data double-counted. This is how Structured Streaming delivers exactly-once processing.

And then the loop closes. With the checkpoint saved, Spark goes right back to the offset tracker and asks again, what's new? The next micro-batch begins, and the cycle repeats forever.

So hold this single picture in your head. Streaming is batch, plus a loop, plus four additions. Offsets to track what's new, a trigger to decide when to run, a state store to remember across batches, and a checkpoint to recover from failure. Strip those four away and you're left with the ordinary batch job you already know. That's the beauty of it, you didn't have to learn a new Spark, you just learned to run the old one in a circle.
